<span id="freeTextContainer81189210482722668">I only read &quot;The Seagull&quot; this time around. Have read &quot;The Cherry Orchard&quot; and &quot;Uncle Vanya&quot; previously. Will have to get to &quot;Three Sisters&quot; another day.<br/><br/>One thing I liked was that this was an up-to-date American translation. No musty period pieces here. This helped bring out the farcial aspects of the play. After all, Chekhov himself called it &quot;A Comedy in Four Acts.&quot; Plus, &quot;The Seagull&quot; contains (part of) a play within the play, which is very easy to mock.<br/><br/>Overall, not as strong as his later wor</span>
  <span id="freeText81189210482722668" style="display:none">I only read "The Seagull" this time around. Have read "The Cherry Orchard" and "Uncle Vanya" previously. Will have to get to "Three Sisters" another day.<br /><br />One thing I liked was that this was an up-to-date American translation. No musty period pieces here. This helped bring out the farcial aspects of the play. After all, Chekhov himself called it "A Comedy in Four Acts." Plus, "The Seagull" contains (part of) a play within the play, which is very easy to mock.<br /><br />Overall, not as strong as his later works--no surprise there--but he was already deft with characterization. If you've read other stuff by Chekhov and enjoyed it, I'd recommend it. If you're new to him, it might be better to start with "Uncle Vanya" or some of the short stories.</span>
