    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3483725797" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3483725797" />
    <a title="Todd Hogan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/50266760-todd-hogan"><img alt="Todd Hogan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1595862079p2/50266760.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3483725797?book_show_action=true">Aug 29, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Todd Hogan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Todd Hogan" href="/user/show/50266760-todd-hogan">Todd Hogan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780810110489" href="/book/show/87334.Chekov_for_the_Stage">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3483725797" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2053744947606418508">This is a convenient starting place to read the four major Anton Chekhov plays, &quot;The Seagull,&quot; &quot;Three Sisters,&quot; &quot;Uncle Vanya,&quot; and &quot;The Cherry Orchard.&quot; However, there is so much to explore in each of Chekhov&apos;s plays that I wish there were more author&apos;s notes to help explain the text. I read another version of just one of the plays, &quot;The Cherry Orchard,&quot; and learned about the history of the period, the characters&apos; symbolism, the complexity of each individual character (they are each pulled in di</span>
  <span id="freeText2053744947606418508" style="display:none">This is a convenient starting place to read the four major Anton Chekhov plays, "The Seagull," "Three Sisters," "Uncle Vanya," and "The Cherry Orchard." However, there is so much to explore in each of Chekhov's plays that I wish there were more author's notes to help explain the text. I read another version of just one of the plays, "The Cherry Orchard," and learned about the history of the period, the characters' symbolism, the complexity of each individual character (they are each pulled in different directions), and the economic status of Russia at the time. All of these elements are vital to a more complete understanding of the plays and appreciation of Chekhov's art.<br /><br />So, although this is a good place to jump into the plays, don't stop there. At a minimum, check out you-tube videos of the performances or the actors discussing their roles. Pick up another version of the plays to read a different translation. For example, Russian slang (which Chekhov is unafraid to include) is notoriously difficult to convert to American idiom. But it's fun to see what the translator has attempted.<br /><br />Beyond the translation issues, you still are able to enjoy the mystery of these characters. Some of the mystery resides in the depths of the philosophical Russian soul, or the conversion from Master and Servant to Independent Entrepreneurs. The Industrial Revolution was occurring in backwards Russia at the time, the Russian Revolution had not yet occurred. So, the reader must understand not modern Russia, but Tsarist Russia to appreciate the conflicts.<br /><br />Chekhov is a humanist, interested in the individual's struggles in life. These plays demonstrate his interests and the depth of his insights. They are not easy reads, but they reward an imaginative mind.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2053744947606418508" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

