<span id="freeTextContainer4092877329930821189">The Cherry Orchard<br/><br/>This play is about a once wealthy family that has fallen on hard times and is now forced to sell its estate, including the eponymous cherry orchard. It represents a changing economy and emphasises both the sadness and liberty that comes with endings. &quot;Mamochka&quot; is a generous but sentimental woman who let&apos;s her heart make the (often poor) decisions. Her brother Gayev is a talkative and fairly cheerful man. Lopakhin is a rich merchant whose family once worked as serfs on the esta</span>
  <span id="freeText4092877329930821189" style="display:none">The Cherry Orchard<br /><br />This play is about a once wealthy family that has fallen on hard times and is now forced to sell its estate, including the eponymous cherry orchard. It represents a changing economy and emphasises both the sadness and liberty that comes with endings. "Mamochka" is a generous but sentimental woman who let's her heart make the (often poor) decisions. Her brother Gayev is a talkative and fairly cheerful man. Lopakhin is a rich merchant whose family once worked as serfs on the estate. Other characters include the workaholic Varya, money-minded Pishchik, the old servant Firs, Petya "the eternal student" and Yasha the irreverent young servant.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4092877329930821189" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
